55–1393","1364–1405":"1364–1405","1305–1379":"1305–1379","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","12 July 1355":"12 July 1355","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1327":"1327","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1364":"1364","12 April 1393":"12 April 1393","1409":"1409","about 1364":"about 1364","1328":"1328","1405":"1405","Mottram St Andrew, Cheshire, England":"Mottram St Andrew, Cheshire, England","Lea by Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Nantwich, Cheshire, England","Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England":"Lea by Backford, Cheshire, England","Mottram, Cheshire, England":"Mottram, Cheshire, England","Broxton, Cheshire, England":"Broxton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mottram","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places in Cheshire, Mottram Saint Andrew or, less probably, Mottram in Longdendale. The placenames may derive from Old English <i>mōt-trēum</i> ‘at the assembly trees’ (from <i>mōt</i> ‘meeting, assembly’ + <i>trēum</i>, dative plural of <i>trēow</i> ‘tree’) or <i>mōterum</i> ‘at the speakers’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":1,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":10,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":55,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Mottram was born in 1327, in Mottram St Andrew, Cheshire, England, her father, Adam Mottram, was 22 and her mother, Ellen Somerford, was 18. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with David De Calveley. She died in 1394, in Broxton, Cheshire, England, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1327–1394":"1327–1394","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1350–1409":"1350–1409","1355–1393":"1355–1393","1364–1405":"1364–1405","1305–1379":"1305–1379","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","12 July 1355":"12. juuli 1355","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1327":"1327","1305":"1305","1337":"133